    "markdown": "## MRI Bilateral Temporal Bone / Inner Ear Without Contrast Overview\n\n### Quick Snapshot: What the Scan Does\n- \\*\\*Purpose:\\*\\* Visualises the cochlea, vestibule, semi-circular canals, auditory nerve and surrounding bone structures.\n- \\*\\*No contrast:\\*\\* Safer for patients with kidney issues or dye allergies.\n- \\*\\*Duration:\\*\\* 25–35 minutes total appointment time.\n### Why Choose Cadabams Diagnostics\n- \\*\\*3T MRI scanners\\*\\* for sharper detail than standard 1.5T machines.\n- \\*\\*Same-day digital reports\\*\\* sent to your phone and referring doctor.\n- \\*\\*Comfort-first approach:\\*\\* Wide-bore design, music headphones and optional mild sedation.\n\n## Risks & Limitations\n\n- \\*\\*No radiation risk\\*\\* – MRI uses magnetic fields, not X-rays.\n- \\*\\*Limitations:\\*\\* Small inflammatory changes may be less visible than with contrast.\n- \\*\\*Contraindications:\\*\\*\n- Pacemakers or cochlear implants (unless MRI-conditional)\n- Severe \\*\\*claustrophobia\\*\\* (we offer sedation)\n- First-trimester pregnancy (discuss with radiologist)\n\n## List of Parameters Considered During This MRI Scan\n\n| Parameter | What We Check | Why It Matters |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cochlear nerve calibre | Thickness & signal | Rules out compression or tumour |\n| Semi-circular canal integrity | Shape & fluid signal | Diagnoses BPPV or canal dehiscence |\n| Middle ear ossicles | Malleus, incus, stapes | Detects erosion or fixation |\n| Internal auditory canal (IAC) diameter | Width & symmetry | Early sign of acoustic neuroma |\n\n## Reasons for Taking a Bilateral Temporal Bone / Inner Ear MRI Without Contrast\n\n- \\*\\*Unexplained hearing loss or tinnitus\\*\\* – identify tumours or malformations.\n- \\*\\*Vertigo or balance disorders\\*\\* – visualise inner-ear fluid dynamics.\n- \\*\\*Post-traumatic facial palsy\\*\\* – check for temporal bone fracture.\n\n## Opting for an MRI Bilateral Temporal Bone / Inner Ear Without Contrast at Cadabams Diagnostics offers several significant benefits in your diagnostic journey:\n\n- \\*\\*Early detection of acoustic neuroma\\*\\* – improves treatment outcomes.\n- \\*\\*Non-invasive and painless\\*\\* – no needles or radiation.\n- \\*\\*Same-day digital reports\\*\\* – faster specialist consultation.\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with a Temporal Bone & Inner Ear MRI (Without Contrast)\n\n- \\*\\*Acoustic neuroma / vestibular schwannoma\\*\\* – benign nerve-sheath tumour.\n- \\*\\*Meniere’s disease\\*\\* – endolymphatic hydrops.\n- \\*\\*Labyrinthitis\\*\\* – viral or bacterial inflammation.\n- \\*\\*Cholesteatoma\\*\\* – cystic mass eroding bone.\n\n## Preparing for Your MRI Bilateral Temporal Bone / Inner Ear Without Contrast\n\n- \\*\\*Fasting not required\\*\\* – eat and drink normally.\n- \\*\\*Remove all metallic objects\\*\\* – jewellery, hairpins, hearing aids.\n- \\*\\*Inform about implants\\*\\* – pacemaker, aneurysm clips, or tattoos with metallic ink.\n---\n## Pre-requisites\n- \\*\\*Signed MRI safety checklist\\*\\* – completed on arrival.\n- \\*\\*Recent audiometry report\\*\\* – bring if available; helps correlate findings.\n---\n## Best Time to Take the MRI Bilateral Temporal Bone / Inner Ear Without Contrast\n- \\*\\*Morning slots\\*\\* – shorter wait times and fresher staff.\n- \\*\\*Book 24–48 h in advance\\*\\* – secure your preferred slot via our app or website.\n---\n## Eligibility\n- \\*\\*Adults and children over 5 years\\*\\* – paediatric sedation available.\n- \\*\\*No renal function restrictions\\*\\* – no contrast means no GFR blood test needed.\n---\n## Procedure for Taking a MRI Bilateral Temporal Bone / Inner Ear Without Contrast\n1. \\*\\*Check-in & safety screening\\*\\* (~10 min)\n2. \\*\\*Positioning in 3T scanner\\*\\* – lie on your back, head in a cushioned cradle (~30 min scan)\n3. \\*\\*Post-scan image QC & digital upload\\*\\* – radiologist reviews images immediately.\n---\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\n- \\*\\*Notify staff of pregnancy\\*\\* – especially first trimester.\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobic patients\\*\\* – request mild oral sedation (requires accompanying adult)."
